EIGHTH-GRADE HONOREES ASSURE
GREAT YEAR AHEAD FOR DEL VAL HIGH

Each spring, Delaware Valley High School asks its sending middle schools to pick out their top eighth-graders and send them to an Eighth Grade Honors Recognition Ceremony in the high school cafeteria. Each spring, that is, except this one.

The event was attended by each honorees' parents, principal and favorite teacher, who would make an introductory speech. This exercise welcomes these promising new students, while reassuring the Del Val administration of a great year to come.

Despite the pandemic, “we did not want to overlook a 30-year tradition,” said Del Val Superintendent Daria Wasserbach, so “on June 1, our eighth-grade honorees were delivered gift bags with some Del Val swag and were presented with a video tribute.”

The video contains the names and photos of this select company of next fall's ninth-graders, along with the written-out plaudits of their favorite teachers.

Here's the link:
https://youtu.be/7itX5J30SkM

-Rick Epstein

VFW COMMANDER AWARDS SCHOLARSHIPS
TO DEL VAL'S HUBER, OLCOTT AND FAWTHROP

Several Veterans of Foreign Wars and at least one Legionnaire convened Monday, June 8, in the Del Val High School driveway to salute the winners of VFW essay contest scholarships and to award signing bonuses to three other seniors.

Handing out the envelopes was Milford VFW commander and Vietnam vet Sonny Silva.

Writing the best essay on “The True Cost of Freedom” was Jessica Huber, winning a $2,500 scholarship; second was Hayden Olcott, for $1,500; and third was MacKenzie Fawthrop, for $1,000.

The VFW also gives $300 to each senior who was signed up for military service. This money is going to Joshua Adams and Andrew Marino for joining the Army, and Andrew Larsen for Army Reserves. MacKenzie plans to join Navy ROTC at college, so Mr. Silva indicated she could get a check after some formalities.

The venue was chosen for its proximity to the flags representing each branch of the military.

post_text:
SENIORS RECEIVING SPECIAL DELIVERIES

Since Monday, Del Val's board president Ellen Gordon-Obal, Superintendent Daria Wasserbach and Principal Adrienne Olcott have been making house calls -- more precisely driveway calls -- to each Del Val senior.

They are delivering caps and gowns, senior awards, varsity blankets, gifts and other items to each member of the Class of 2020 in advance of the June 12 drive-thru graduation rites. They hope to finish up tomorrow.

At the wheel of the festively bannered school bus is Transportation Director Jerry Ford.

Yes there are masks. No there are no hugs or handshakes. But students and parents were generally delighted by this effort to make an occasion of this year's graduation, despite the pandemic constraints.

Here is the first of many installments of photos from this four-day mission. There are a lot of photos because the photographer was operating under a No-QuarantineMate-Left-Behind directive.

post_text:
NJ.com SALUTES RUNNER KYLE REERS
FOR SEASON THAT MIGHT HAVE BEEN

Del Val's speed demon Kyle Reers has been named to NJ.com's all-senior boys' track and field second team, as the news organization laid a wreath on the altar of What Might Have Been.

That is to say, that despite the pandemic “NJ.com wanted to make sure the state's top senior runners, throwers, hurdlers and pole vaulters received their due...”

The heartbroken sportswriters listed “Kyle Reers, Delaware Valley, 400 IH (Intermediate Hurdles)” above these bullet points:

- 800 and 400 IH indoor group champion and 3rd in 800 MOC (Meet of Champions) with PR (personal record) of 1:52.81
- 1st in outdoor group 800 with PR of 1:55.01 as a junior
- 4th in outdoor MOC 400 hurdles as a junior with a PR of 52.59

A few months ago Kyle signed a letter of intent to run for the University of South Carolina.

-Rick Epstein

post_text:
SLUGGER BRIANNA BARBADORA
NAMED TO COURIER'S ALL-AREA TEAM

Del Val's Brianna Barbadora has been named to the Courier News' Softball Senior All-Area Team, even though the pandemic has robbed her – and everyone else – of their 2020 spring season. And there's no rain check for that.

The Courier (mycentraljersey.com) just took last year's stats and made the logical assumption that Barbadora would be crushing it in '20.

They wrote: “The left fielder hit .429 with six doubles, four triples, a homer and 29 RBIs last season, scoring 24 times for the Valley Division champs and HWST runners-up in her first season as a full-time varsity starter. She'll play at Moravian next year.”

Amanda Monda received honorable mention.

DEL VAL STUDENTS, STAFF, FAMILIES
TO PERFORM IN QUARAN-TALENT SHOW

Two of our more effervescent teachers are instigating a Del Val Quaran-Talent Stay @ Home Showcase. Billy Gregson of DVTV and Brian Smith, adviser to The Delphi, are inviting students, staff, and their families to submit videos of themselves performing their talents to thedelphi@dvrhs.k12.nj.us by May 22 to be included in the show.

They announced jointly: “Whether it be song, dance, comedy, or anything in between, they want to showcase all of the talent that Del Val has to offer. There is no time limit on acts, and there are no auditions. If you want to be in the show, you're in! Help us celebrate all that Del Val has to offer!”

The show will premiere on DVTV's YouTube page at 7 p.m. on Friday, May 29.

THE POPE SISTERS EXPRESS GRATITUDE
TO HUNTERDON HEALTHCARE WORKERS

Del Val senior Alexis Pope saw that Hunterdon Medical Center sent out a request for signs/posters to encourage its healthcare providers, who are bravely carrying on during the pandemic.

So Alexis and her sister Isabella, who will be a Del Val freshman in the fall, thought to make small, personalized sized signs as well as poster-sized signs. These pictures were taken by their grandmother, Rita Pope, on her front lawn in Milford. The girls wanted to show her (while practicing social distancing) the posters before they mailed them to HMC.

The girls really hope that this encourages them and hope that they know that we are all so grateful for what they are doing.

post_text:
SPORTS BANQUETS CANCELED;
DEL VAL ATHLETIC DIRECTOR
SALUTES SEVERAL STANDOUTS

The Covid-19 crisis has canceled a number of sports banquets at which Del Val athletes would have been honored for excellence on the field and in the classroom.

Those organizations and the Terrier honorees are: Skyland Conference, cheerleader Catherine Cunningham and cross country and track runner Kyle Reers; Hunterdon/Warren/Sussex conference, Kevin Burns for cross country and lacrosse, and Shea Cinquemani for field hockey; and NJSIAA, Shelby Pyatt for basketball.

"This has been a super-frustrating time for everyone, but especially for our athletes," said Del Val Athletic Director Bill Deniz. "Our spring athletes may lose a season, and others like Catherine, Kyle, Kevin, Shea and Shelby are missing out on these banquets. But I hope they know we are all proud of them."

-Rick Epstein

REERS NAMED “ALL AMERICAN”
AFTER VIRUS CANCELS NATIONALS

Del Val’s top distance runner Kyle Reers is one of many athletes who've been thwarted by Covid-19 precautions. But his situation was particularly frustrating. He had qualified for the nationals, scheduled for March 13-15.

He recently received a letter from the sponsoring organization, the National Scholastic Athletic Foundation, that said, “While we regret that we had no choice but to cancel the New Balance Nationals, we do not want your season accomplishments to be overlooked.”

After examining his achievements so far, the NSAF named Kyle an “All American” and sent him a certificate and a shirt.

His March 8 performance at the state Meet of Champions had him ranked No. 3 in New Jersey and No. 8 In the U.S. in this event. (That's where he won the medal shown in the photo.) Going into that race, he’d been sixth in the state and 44th in the nation.

In the fall, Kyle will be running for the University of South Carolina.

DISTANCE LEARNING AT DEL VAL
IS TOPIC ON WDVR-FM AT 6 TONIGHT

Del Val's ongoing adventures in distance learning will be discussed on WDVR-FM radio today, March 31, between 6 and 6:30 p.m.

The program will be about how libraries and schools are adapting to the current health crisis by harnessing the Internet. The Hunterdon County Library will be represented by Jennifer Winberry; the Holland Township Library, by Jan Rower; and Del Val High School by Superintendent Daria Wasserbach and director of curriculum Mike Gurysh.

It will be hosted by WDVR broadcaster Math Westlake, Del Val Class of '03, who is also supervising librarian of the Holland library.

WDVR is a nonprofit radio station based in Sergeantsville.

post_text:
KYLE REERS RUNS EVEN FASTER
AT MEET OF CHAMPIONS; HE IS
NOW 3RD IN STATE, 8TH IN NATION

Del Val’s speed demon Kyle Reers placed third in the 800-meter race at the Meet of Champions on Sunday, March 8, at the Ocean Breeze Complex in Staten Island with a time of 1:52.81.

Kyle is now ranked No. 3 in New Jersey and No. 8 In the U.S. in this event. Going into that race, he’d been sixth in the state and 44th in the nation.

He will now compete on Sunday, March 15, at Nationals, which will be held at The Armory in New York City.

He has privately trained for this for many months and really devoted himself to achieving this!” said Sue Coles, his volunteer faculty adviser. “In just a week's time between the Group Championship and the Meet of Champions, he improved his time by 3 seconds, which is an amazing accomplishment!

“He is a very smart runner and knows how to plan his strategy as to where to position himself and when to start his final kick in the race,” she said.

DEL VAL’S MUSICAL “CATCH ME IF YOU CAN”
IN FINAL PERFORMANCES FRIDAY & SATURDAY

Delaware Valley High School’s musical “Catch Me If You Can” opened last week and will be presented twice more – at 7 p.m. on Friday, March 13, and Saturday, March 14.

It stars Thai Branowski as Frank Abignale Jr., a young con man who masquerades as an airline pilot and a doctor, while raking in millions with forged checks. In relentless pursuit is FBI agent Carl Hanratty, played by Hunter Trstensky. Both are veterans of the Del Val stage.

Admission costs $12. Reserve tickets by contacting theater@dvrhs.org, or buy them at the door.

SENIOR CITIZENS LOVED IT! DEL VAL MUSICAL
CONTINUES WITH SHOWS MARCH 6, 7, 13, 14

Delaware Valley High School’s musical “Catch Me If You Can” made a strong opening last evening with a preview show, and considering that it was a senior-citizen show, there was a lot of appreciative hollering. A standing ovation, too!

One senior citizen said, “After exposure to so much energy, excitement and talent running riot on the stage, I had to go home and lie down with a cool cloth on my forehead.”

The first regular shows are tonight (Friday) and tomorrow (Saturday) at 2 p.m. and 7 p.m. Tickets are available.

The show goes on twice more the following weekend -- Friday, March 13, and Saturday, March 14, both shows at 7 p.m.

Admission costs $12. Reserve tickets by contacting theater@dvrhs.org, or buy them at the door.

-Rick Epstein

Delaware Valley High School’s musical “Catch Me If You Can” made a strong opening last evening with a preview show, and considering that it was a senior-citizen show, there was a lot of appreciative hollering. A standing ovation, too!

One senior citizen said, “After exposure to so much energy, excitement and talent running riot on the stage, I had to go home and lie down with a cool cloth on my forehead.”

The first regular shows are tonight (Friday) and tomorrow (Saturday) at 2 p.m. and 7 p.m. Tickets are available.

The show goes on twice more the following weekend -- Friday, March 13, and Saturday, March 14, both shows at 7 p.m.

Admission costs $12. Reserve tickets by contacting theater@dvrhs.org, or buy them at the door.

-Rick Epstein

post_text:
NURSE CHRIS GRAND IS DEL VAL’S
MARCH EMPLOYEE OF THE MONTH

Chris Grand, Del Val’s leave-replacement nurse, was named Employee of the Month at Monday’s faculty meeting by Principal Adrienne Olcott.

Mrs. Grand’s service to the school became conspicuous recently when a student went into anaphylactic shock. Mrs. Olcott said that Mrs. Grand responded to the emergency with extreme calm, competence and kindness.

Mrs. Grand is a Registered Nurse. She has worked in various hospitals, and for 15 years was a school nurse at Hunterdon Central High School. Last year she was a substitute nurse for Del Val, gaining full-time temporary status last November.

-Rick Epstein

KYLE REERS IS NEW JERSEY’S GROUP 1
CHAMPION IN 800-METER RACE

Del Val’s Kyle Reers continues to tear up the winter track. This time – Feb. 29 – he won the Group 1 championship for the entire state in the 800-meter race. Competing at Toms River, he set a new Group 1 record with a time of 1:55.98.

His next event will be the Meet of Champions on Sunday, March 8, at the Ocean Breeze Athletic Complex on Staten Island.

Although he is a senior, Kyle’s high school running career has one more season to go. He’ll be running on the Track and Field team in the spring.

STUDENT OF THE MONTH

Del Val’s Student of the Month is Walter Heiser, a junior from Holland Township.

In presenting Walter to the school board at its Feb. 24 meeting, Principal Adrienne Olcott praised his positivity. But it was an act of compassion that precipitated his selection as Student of the Month.

A special-needs student was acting out in a physical way, and Walter stepped in to contain and gently de-escalate the situation.

Del Val recognizes a variety of students at each monthly board meeting -- for their achievements in sports, the arts, and, as in the case of Walter Heiser, in the realm of human interaction.

-Rick Epstein

KYLE REERS IS SECTIONAL GROUP 1
CHAMP IN 800-METER RACE

Del Val’s Kyle Reers has won the Group 1 championship in the 800-meter race in the NJSIAA Sectionals in Toms River, with a time of 1:55:97.

He will compete again in the Groups this Saturday. New Jersey is divided into four geographical sections, and the high schools are divided into groups based on enrollment. No matter how he does this Saturday, he has already qualified to run in the Nationals.

Although he is a senior, Kyle’s high school running career has one more season to go; all that winter work has him primed for Track and Field in the spring.

“Kyle is one of the most self-disciplined student athletes I have ever come across,” said Sue Coles, his volunteer faculty adviser. “He is dedicated, determined and loves to set and achieve goals! He is a 100 percent kind of person.”

She added that “he is also very funny and a pleasure to be around. Both his peers and his coaches enjoy his company! I will certainly miss him next year and wish him all the best at the University of South Carolina!”

FIVE TERRIER ATHLETES SIGN
COLLEGE LETTERS OF INTENT

Five Del Val athletes have agreed to attend colleges that want them to bring their minds and bodies to their campuses in the fall.

Signing letters of intent in the media center yesterday were:

Kyle Reers, track and cross country, University of South Carolina; Deborah Nalesnik, field hockey, Allegheny College; Brianna Barbadora, softball, Moravian College; Hayden Olcott, lacrosse, Gwynedd Mercy College; and Charles Niebuhr, lacrosse, Ithaca College. Kyle, Deborah and Brianna are from Holland Township, and Hayden and Charles are from Alexandria Township.

The event, hosted by Athletic Director Bill Deniz, consisted of signatures, photographs with smiling parents and coaches, and a round of applause.

-Rick Epstein

post_text:
ERIN KRAUS IS DEL VAL’S
EMPLOYEE OF THE MONTH

Erin (Critelli) Kraus was named Del Val Employee of the Month at Monday’s faculty meeting.

She is a paraprofessional doing “a fantastic job with special-needs kids,” said Principal Adrienne Olcott in making the announcement. Her positivity and eagerness to help out were cited. Mrs. Kraus started at Del Val in 2016.

Frank Guenther, director of special services, echoed Mrs. Olcott’s sentiments, adding that Mrs. Kraus arrives early and stays late, “making herself available to the kids.” He praised her kindness and her willingness to take on the most-demanding assignments. She never complains and needs very little direction, Dr. Guenther said.

He also noted that she is equally generous with her time and energy outside of school, having been a Raritan Township firefighter for the past 10 years.

Also applauded at the faculty meeting was art teacher Sarah Ruppert, who came to Del Val four years ago and has now achieved tenure.

-Rick Epstein

DEL VAL NEEDS BUS DRIVERS;
WILL TRAIN AND PAY WELL

Del Val High School needs bus drivers. If you are licensed to drive a school bus, that’s great. But if don’t have a CDL-B, we’ll train you and help you get it.

The pay is $23.26 an hour if we train you or $24.19 if you already have the CDL-B school bus license.

The daily hours are roughly 6-9 a.m. and 2-4:30 p.m. Drivers are also eligible to drive to athletic events after school and on weekends if they want to.

Transportation director Jerry Ford says, “Our buses are easy to drive. They have automatic transmission, lots of mirrors, and with power steering and power brakes, you'd think it was the family SUV.” As additional benefits, he cites paid sick and personal days, plus beautiful countryside to drive through.

All drivers must pass a physical, be fingerprinted and pass a criminal background check and pre-employment drug test, with Del Val paying those associated fees.

To learn more or to arrange an interview, call 908-996-4385.

post_text:
HOLLAND’S SANDRA HOWELL IS THANKED
FOR DECADE ON DEL VAL SCHOOL BOARD

Sandra Howell, who has just finished representing Holland Township on the Del Val school board, was honored at the Jan. 27 meeting for her decade of service.

Board president Ellen Gordon-Obal said, “Sandy always challenged us to think critically, to take data into consideration, and always, always, always do right for the students. That was her number one goal. What I might think is right for the students, someone else might think is wrong. But everybody worked together and we came to a consensus… I will keep your past comments and what I learned from you in all my decision-making.”

Dr. Howell acknowledged her own dissenting opinions and said she’d always advocated for theater and the arts, making sure that those “shining stars” got their due “in a very sporty Del Val.”

Superintendent Daria Wasserbach added her thanks for Dr. Howell’s distinguished service.

DEL VAL SALUTES BASKETBALL CENTER
KAITLIN O’BOYLE, ATHLETE OF THE MONTH

Del Val’s Athlete of the Month is Kaitlin O’Boyle, a sophomore from Kingwood Township. She was honored at Monday’s school board meeting.

Kaitlyn is the starting center on the basketball team, and her coach, Mike Haughey, is mightily pleased to have her early talent, excellent attitude, with two more seasons to develop her potential.

At the meeting, Coach Haughey praised her “great personality” and said she “brings life to our team. She’s a sparkplug for our team. The girls gravitate to her; they’re buying what she’s selling. She works hard at her craft, and plays basketball in season and out of season. Her future is really bright here.”

The male Athlete of the Month is another sophomore basketball player -- Logan Blake. But since he was unable to attend the board meeting, he’ll have his moment in the spotlight next month.

-Rick Epstein

GINGERBREAD-HOUSE DECORATING
CONTEST HOSTED BY DIVERSITY CLUB

The Diversity Club’s Dec. 13 gingerbread-house-decorating contest was won by Madi Beyers, Hannah Hirsch, Katie Croasdale and Anna De Leao.

Thirty-eight students came to the Media Center, where each of 10 teams, consisting of two to four students, was issued a small gingerbread house. Each house had been prefabbed by club president Shea Cinquemani and club adviser Lisa Cartwright.

Each team was equipped with gumdrops, frosting and other appropriately colorful material; and given 15 minutes to work their magic. The tight deadline added an element of manic urgency to the process.

Then the creations were evaluated by a panel of gingerbread-house experts from Janice Jones’ class. The winning team was planning to present their house to math teacher Ryan Murphy. Note to Mr. Murphy: Eat around the joinery; the house was glued together.

-Rick Epstein

LOCKTOWN CONCERT GAVE A PREVIEW PEEK
AT DEC. 12 WINTER CONCERT AT DEL VAL

The fundraising concert on Dec. 6 at the Locktown Stone Church gave a preview of the vocal part of the Thursday, Dec. 12, Del Val Winter Concert – while raising about $1,500 for the music department’s upcoming trip to Boston.

The old church was packed -- with paying customers, the young vocalists, and choir director Dan Wells, whose enthusiasm causes him to seem larger than his size. Some of the proceeds were from sales by the Performing Arts Boosters of chorus CDs and of refreshments that were all the more refreshing for being served outdoors.

Tomorrow night’s Winter Concert, which is free and starts at 7 p.m. in the Del Val auditorium, is titled "The Moon of Winter," and will take place in the auditorium. It will feature new and old music of the season by Del Val’s many vocal and instrumental music ensembles.

-Rick Epstein
